## Vercel Web Analytics Installation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js project.

### Changes Made:

**1. Installed Package:**
- Added `@vercel/analytics` version 2.0.1 to project dependencies using pnpm
- Package manager: pnpm
- Installation command: `pnpm add @vercel/analytics`

**2. Modified Files:**
- **app/layout.tsx**: Added Analytics component following Next.js App Router best practices
  - Imported `Analytics` from `@vercel/analytics/next`
  - Placed `<Analytics />` component at the end of the `<body>` element
  - Preserved existing code structure including fonts, metadata, and styling

**3. Updated Dependencies:**
- **package.json**: Added @vercel/analytics to dependencies
- **pnpm-lock.yaml**: Updated lockfile with new dependency tree (353 packages added)

### Implementation Details:

The implementation follows the official Vercel Analytics quickstart guide (retrieved from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart).

For Next.js App Router projects, the Analytics component should be:
1. Imported from `@vercel/analytics/next`
2. Placed within the `<body>` element of the root layout
3. Positioned after the main content (children)

### Verification:

✅ Build completed successfully (`pnpm build`)
✅ No linting errors introduced in modified file
✅ TypeScript compilation passed
✅ All 7 static pages and 23 dynamic routes generated correctly

### Next Steps:

To complete the setup:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Enable Analytics in the Vercel project dashboard (Analytics > Enable)
3. After deployment, verify tracking by checking browser Network tab for requests to `/<unique-path>/view`

### Notes:

- The project uses Next.js 16.2.2 with the App Router
- Pre-existing linting errors in other components were not addressed (out of scope)
- The Analytics component will automatically track page views
- Analytics data will be available in the Vercel dashboard after enabling the feature
